{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14356"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14356"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0.75,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7051"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40348"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4397"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit in June. She is 10 weeks pregnant with her first child. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her immunisation history is up to date, except for influenza vaccination. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding influenza vaccination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaccinate only if there is an influenza outbreak","Vaccinate at 20 weeks gestation","Vaccinate immediately","Defer vaccination until after delivery","Vaccinate in the third trimester"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate advice is to \u003Cstrong\u003Evaccinate immediately\u003C/strong\u003E. Influenza vaccination is strongly recommended for all pregnant women at any stage of pregnancy due to the increased risk of severe complications from influenza during pregnancy. The fact that it is June, which is typically the beginning of the influenza season in Australia, makes immediate vaccination even more crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring vaccination until after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it leaves the woman unprotected during pregnancy when she is at higher risk of severe influenza complications. Additionally, vaccination during pregnancy provides passive immunity to the newborn for the first few months of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdvising to \u003Cstrong\u003Evaccinate at 20 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E or to \u003Cstrong\u003Evaccinate in the third trimester\u003C/strong\u003E unnecessarily delays protection. The influenza vaccine is safe and effective when given at any stage of pregnancy, so there is no benefit in waiting, especially as the influenza season is approaching or may have already begun.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccinating only if there is an influenza outbreak\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it may be too late to provide protection once an outbreak occurs. Influenza can circulate at any time of the year, but is more common during winter months in Australia (June to August), making timely vaccination important.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnant women are at higher risk of severe complications from influenza, including hospitalisation and death, compared to non-pregnant women of the same age. This is due to changes in the immune system, heart, and lungs during pregnancy. Influenza during pregnancy also increases the risk of complications for the developing baby, including premature birth and low birth weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe influenza vaccine is safe for both the mother and the developing baby. It does not contain live virus and cannot cause influenza. The antibodies generated by the mother in response to the vaccine cross the placenta, providing passive immunity to the newborn for the first few months of life when they are too young to be vaccinated themselves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Influenza vaccination is strongly recommended for all pregnant women due to the increased risk of severe complications from influenza during pregnancy.","Influenza vaccine can be safely administered at any stage of pregnancy.","Influenza vaccination during pregnancy also provides passive immunity to the newborn for the first few months of life."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Influenza vaccination in pregnancy. College Statement C-Obs 45. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2017. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Influenza-vaccination-in-pregnancy-C-Obs-45-Review-March-2017.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-10T14:23:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T14:25:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":